<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18371023-2452">
               <interp inst="t18371023-2452" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18371023"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18371023-2452" type="date" value="18371023"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18371023-2452-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2452-18371023 t18371023-2452-offence-1 t18371023-2452-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2452. <persName id="def1-2452-18371023" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2452-18371023" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2452-18371023" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2452-18371023" type="surname" value="HAYNES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2452-18371023" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ROBERT HAYNES</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18371023-2452-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18371023-2452-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18371023-2452-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18371023-cd-237" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18371023-2452-offence-1 t18371023-cd-237"></join>15th of July</rs>, 6 1 1/2 yards of lawn, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18371023-name-1609" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1609" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1609" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1609" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18371023-2452-offence-1 t18371023-name-1609"></join>Thomas. Brooks</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1610" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1610" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1610" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1610" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS BROOKS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in High-street, Borough. The prisoner was engaged as porter in my house, by my traveller, about the beginning of June—on the 20th of June I purchased six pieces of lawn at Messrs. Lainson's, in Bread-street—they were deposited in the warehouse—I repeatedly missed goods, and on the 17th of July this one was pawned at a pawn<lb></lb>broker's in the New Cut, it is mine—the selling mark has been rubbed out with india-rubber, but they have left the other mark.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I believe you had other servants? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, a great many—I was here last session against the same boy, and I was positive about the other article—the mark on this is "21<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a yard, and my private mark, in my writing—the moment I saw it at the pawn<lb></lb>broker's I looked for the mark, and they had attempted to deface it—I had a person named Patrick in my employ—nearly the whole of the persons who were in my service then are there now—I have discharged two or three, I think—I have perhaps twenty persons—my private mark is one that no one else has in the trade—it is one of my own making—the lawn in the warehouse was folded up in three pieces of ornamental paper—I think blue paper twice round the ends, and once in the middle—the prisoner was the only person I suspected of this, and till I received informa<lb></lb>tion I had not the slightest suspicion even of him—the prisoner was in my service in June, not before—I had the information from two boys, about the middle of August—he had left me in July, but I took him back again—I had no bad opinion of him—there are six yards of this—here is my own private mark on it, which refers to the cost price, and the 52 the average mark—I had two marks on it, but one has been rubbed out—I remember the result of the trial last Sessions perfectly well—when a woman shook her fist at me, I said, when I could find the boy Goodman he should hear more about it—I said I should have him up here again—I did not say if it would cost me a thousand pounds I would.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was he tried here before for? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> For stealing a shawl, I think.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1611" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1611" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1611" type="surname" value="JENNINGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1611" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES JENNINGS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. Last Tuesday afternoon, at half past four o'clock, I saw the prisoner coming past Newington gate—I had had information from Mr. Brooks that he wished to take him again—I took him—he said, "What is this upon—is it for Mr. Brooks?"—I said, "I believe it is"—he said, "I do not care about that—I have been tried and acquitted about that"—I said, "Do you know that Goodman is at home?"—he said, "There is nobody can hurt me but the boy Goodman"—I said, "You must have had some transactions with him"—he said, "That is to myself."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What was he doing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Dragging a truck—I do not believe he follows any particular occupation—I cannot say that he is a hard working boy.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1612" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1612" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1612" type="surname" value="GOODMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1612" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>WILLIAM HENRY GOODMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I work with my father—he takes in mending and making—I know the prisoner—I used to lodge at his</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183710230255"></xptr>
               <p>mother's—I remember meeting him some time in July—he was carrying a parcel pretty nearly a 1/2cwt.—I went with him to the place and helped him to carry the parcel—in coming back he pulled out a small parcel from his pocket and said, "Will you be so good as to pawn this for me, for Mr. Patrick, as Mr. Patrick has got a summons out against him, and be want this money to pay it"—he gave me 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and I pawned it in the New Cut opposite Rowland Hill's Chapel—I do not know the name of the shop but it was the master who took it—I pawned it for 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—it was a piece of lawn, he told me—I gave him the 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he gave me 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You have come here to speak the truth? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I met him first coming from Mr. Brooks's shop with a parcel—he went to his house and I was at home, and then we went away together—I met him first by the Dover-road, near St. George's Church—I know Surrey-square—that is where I went with the prisoner—it may be more than half a mile from the Borough end of the Dover-road—the first time I met him in the Dover-road he had a heavy weight with him—I went with him to the back of Surrey-square—I did not meet him in the square—he left the parcel at the house—the gentleman was not at home—the lady took it in, and she said there was nobody at home—I had left my work in Suffolk-street then—it was about the 15th of September, I think—I cannot tell—I cannot read—I think it was some time about the election—I never told anybody another day on which I pawned this—it was the day I met him—I think it was July—it was either September or July—he told me to pledge it in the name of John Clark, No. 9, somewhere near Suffolk-street—I think I told the pawnbroker High-street—I got 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—it was a false name and address—I have been sorry since I did it—I have been working lately with my father as a shoemaker, since last Saturday—I went down before that to St. Alban's for a fortnight—I am not known there—before that I was lodg<lb></lb>ing at the prisoner's mother's, working up Suffolk-street at shoemaking—I was about a month there—I had always been with my father before that—I had been to work at different places, and went home to my father—I have worked next door to my father, No. 3, Newington-grove—I have been in a good many situations in Surrey—I know what an oath is—I have worked in Horsemonger-lane jail, because one day I was ill and was very hungry, there was a pair of gaiters, and I took them and got 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to buy some victuals—I was in Horsemonger-lane jail four days and had a flogging.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1613" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1613" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1613" type="surname" value="BURTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1613" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BURTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I took in the lawn in the name of" John Clark," on the 17th of July—I cannot say who pawned it—it was a piece of lawn for 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—it was a boy or a man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You asked him the usual questions? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he said it was for Mr. Clark, who had sent him—he did not say he was sent by his mother, or we should have put it down.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1614" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1614" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1614" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1614" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS BROOKS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> The prisoner was porter to my traveller, and was often left alone in the warehouse where this was.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18371023-2452-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
